1.	What is BFS? 
BFS (Breadth First Search) is a graph traversal algorithm used to visit all nodes level by level starting from a source node. 
	It first visits all neighboring nodes. 
	Then it moves to the next level neighbors. 
	It uses a Queue (FIFO) data structure. 
Steps of BFS 
1.	Start from a source vertex. 
2.	Mark it as visited. 
3.	Insert it into the queue. 
4.	Remove a node from queue and visit all its unvisited neighbors. 
5.	Repeat until queue becomes empty. 
Applications of BFS 
	Shortest path in unweighted graphs 
	Social network analysis 
	Web crawling 
GPS navigation 
	Network broadcasting 
 
